Subject Verification & Vertical Slicing: Scope & Manual UI Tests

Last updated: March 3rd, 2024

Topics: Manual Testing, Scope, E2E, UI interactions, Server Interactions

Finally, in Subject Verification, we confirm the frontend to backend interactions work the way we intend. Of course, we use another manual approach, but instead of testing Server Interactions, we test UI interactions. Not very effective or efficient, but it’s what’s most important at this Phase of Craftship.

Lesson goals

In this lesson, we will:

  • Learn about scope and the two levels we’ve been verifying a Vertical Slice at
  • Recap the problem with manual testing

Essential in Focus: Subject Verification

We’ve made it to the end.

By now, you should have been able to have connected the frontend to the backend, set up the ability to register a new account, cache the result, and redirect to the main page, showing the posts.

Assignment checklist

You’ll see the assignment checklist on the assignment page as well, but while we’re here, start your server, start your UI in dev mode, head to the URL in your browser, and ensure everything here is square.

Assignment Checklist?

Backend

  • 🔘 I have built a getPopularPosts API which returns return the data in the following or similar shape

    • /posts?sort=recent: Gets posts sorted by popularity

    • Example response data:

Frontend

  • 🔘 (Failure case) When I enter invalid account details, I should see a failure Toast

Nice work!

Essential In Focus: Vertical Slicing

Scope

Real quick, let’s make sure we’re on the same page when we talk about scope.

Scope is the height or — in our level of understand now, a particular Horizontal abstraction layer and everything below it.

So, in terms of Subject Verification, you could say we’ve manually applied it to two different levels of scope.

Server to DB

The first level was Server to DB.

And at this level, we used Server Interactions or API calls to test out tiny little Vertical Slices of functionality — basically if the endpoints worked or not.

UI to DB

And backing up in scope even further, from the UI level, we test a series of user interactions.

What does that mean?

It means that the Vertical Slice of functionality is much larger, and basically, this included everything in the system. Much larger chunk of work.

FAQ

What problems might occur here?

Same problems we always have with manual testing:

  • More tests means more to manually test
  • Easy to forget to change the tests
  • Loose feedback loops (can be hard to identify what broke something)

But now, we have two scopes at which we have to keep things in check; that’s going to be tricky.

The key here is to learn how to use automated tests and keep these two scopes in sync.

In BP-First, I’ll introduce you to acceptance tests and we’ll learn how to use them to do just that.

What about E2E (end-to-end)? How does that relate to scope?

E2e can mean either level of scope — it really depends on the context.

For example, if you’re a frontend developer, perhaps an E2E test for you would involve a boundary around the frontend only, perhaps mocking out the API calls.

And if you were a backend developer, an E2E test for you could involve just involve a boundary around the backend API and any other connected systems as well.

And if you were fullstack, perhaps the most straightforward is to say an E2E test is one that executes against the entirety of the stack, from UI to DB with nothing mocked or stubbed out. Real.

All in all, it’s subjective. This is why I find the idea of The Guess Points and using Systems Thinking to break apart how we think about testing, levels of tests & how we make sense of the boundaries.

We’ll get there in Value-First.
